    INTENSIVE JAPANESE AT THE UNIVERSITY OF PITTSBURGH THIS SUMME    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^The University of Pittsburgh is offering two intensive Japanese languagcourses this summer.  Both courses, Intensive Elementary Japanese andIntensive Intermediate Japanese, are ten week, ten credit courseseach equivalent to one full year of Japanese language study.  They beginJune 7 and end August 13.  The courses meet five days per week, five hoursper day.  There is a flat rate tuition charge of $1600 per course. Fellowships available for science and engineering students.  ContactSteven Brener, Program Manager of the Japanese Science and TechnologManagement Program, at the University of Pittsburgh at the number oaddress below. ALL INTERESTED INDIVIDUALS ARE ENCOURAGED TO APPLY, THIS IS NOT LIMITED TOUNIVERSITY STUDENTS #######################################################################################   New Program Announcement   #############################################################################################            JAPANESE SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY MANAGEMENT PROGRAThe Japanese Science and Technology Management Program (JSTMP) is a neprogram jointly developed by the University of Pittsbugh and Carnegie MellonUniversity.  Students and professionals in the engineering and scientificcommunitites are encouraged to apply for classes commencing in June 1993 andJanuary 1994PROGRAM OBJECTIVEThe program intends to promote technology transfer between Japan and theUnited States.  It is also designed to let scientists, engineers, and managerexperience how the Japanese proceed with technological development.  This isfacilitated by extended internships in Japanese research facilities anlaboratories that provide participants with the opportunity to develolong-term professional relationships with their Japanese counterpartsPROGRAM DESIGTo fulfill the objectives of the program, participants will be required todevelop advanced language capability and a deep understanding of Japan anits culture.  Correspondingly, JSTMP consists of three major components1. TRAINING IN THE JAPANESE LANGUAGSeveral Japanese language courses will be offered, including intensive coursedesigned to expedite language preparation for scientists and engineers in relatively short time2. EDUCATION IN JAPANESE BUSINESS AND SOCIAL CULTURA particular enphasis is placed on attaining a deep understanding of thcultural and educational basis of Japanese management approaches inmanufacturing and information technology.  Courses will be available in avariety of departments throughout both universities including AnthropologySociology, History, and Political Science.  Moreover, seminars and colloquiumwill be conducted.  Further, a field trip to Japanese manufacturing orresearch facilities in the United States will be scheduled3. AN INTERNSHIP OR A STUDY MISSION IN JAPAUpon completion of their language and cultural training at PITT and CMU,participants will have the opportunity to go to Japan and observeand participate in the management of technology.  Internships in Japawill generally run for one year; however, shorter ones are possibleFELLOWSHIPS COVERING TUITION FOR LANGUAGE AND CULTURE COURSES, AS WELL ASTIPENDS FOR LIVING EXPENSES ARE AVAILABLE        FOR MORE INFORMATION AND APPLICATION MATERIALS CONTACSTEVEN BRENER\t\t\t\tSUSIE BROWJSTMP\t\t\t\t\tCarnegie Mellon University, GSIUniversity of Pittsburgh\t\tPittsburgh, PA 15213-3894E25 Forbes Quadrangle\t\t\tTelephone: (412) 268-780Pittsburgh, PA 15260\t\t\tFAX:\t   (412) 268-816Telephone: (412) 648-7414\t\FAX:       (412) 648-2199\t\#######################################################################################################################################################Interested individuals, companies and institutions should respond by phone omail.  Please do not inquire via e-mailPlease note that this is directed at grads and professionals, however, advanceundergrads wi